solution_03_central_limit_theorem/01_standard_normal/09_z_from_twotail_area_v2

video

Start with a sketch. The total two-tail area is 0.66, so each tail has half that area.


Method 1: Determine the area of each tail and the center. Both tails have the same area, and all three areas add to 1. Thus, \[P(Z>z) = \frac{0.66}{2} = 0.33\]

\[P(Z<-z) = \frac{0.66}{2} = 0.33\]

\[\begin{aligned} P(|Z|<z) &= 1-P(|Z|>z) \\ &= 1-0.66 \\ &= 0.34 \end{aligned}\]

Find the left area.

\[\begin{aligned} P(Z<z) &= 0.33+0.34 \\ &= 0.67 \end{aligned}\]

You should go to your \(z\)-table and find the \(z\)-score with the left area closest to 0.67.

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
0.41 0.6591
0.42 0.6628
0.43 0.6664
0.44 0.67
0.45 0.6736
0.46 0.6772

It turns out the exact answer is \(z=0.4399132\), which could be found by using an inverse normal function. On a spreadsheet:

=Norm.Inv(0.67,0,1)

Using R:

twotailarea = 0.66
onetailarea = twotailarea/2
centralarea = 1-twotailarea
leftarea = onetailarea + centralarea
qnorm( leftarea )

Method 2: Another way to get 0.67 is by subtracting half of 0.66 from 1. \[P(Z<z) ~=~ 1-\frac{0.66}{2}~=~ 1-0.33 ~=~ 0.67\]


Then, use the table. Or, R:

twotailarea = 0.66
leftarea = 1 - twotailarea/2
qnorm( leftarea )

You might find a spinner visualization useful.
